        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1665368602" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14965020591708898523">When a book series starts off great but then ends with a book like this I am just left wondering &quot;why?&quot;. When death is completely negated for all intents and purposes every time one of the good guys dies than why should the reader care about what&apos;s going on with the story? All tension is completely lost if no matter what, the good guys don&apos;t stay dead! <br/><br/>On that note I&apos;d also like to point out that the whole thing about how a women&apos;s role was simply to provide masculine energy or whatnot to males </span>
  <span id="freeText14965020591708898523" style="display:none">When a book series starts off great but then ends with a book like this I am just left wondering "why?". When death is completely negated for all intents and purposes every time one of the good guys dies than why should the reader care about what's going on with the story? All tension is completely lost if no matter what, the good guys don't stay dead! <br /><br />On that note I'd also like to point out that the whole thing about how a women's role was simply to provide masculine energy or whatnot to males was just so cringeworthy to read. And don't get me started on the haloes that the women need because they apparently can't defend themselves in any meaningful way as compared to males....well ok then!<br /><br />I should've just stopped reading the series after the first book. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14965020591708898523" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
