<div id="review_738104380" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/738104380" />
    <a title="Laura" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23135070-laura"><img alt="Laura" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1561398850p2/23135070.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/738104380?book_show_action=true">Oct 09, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura" href="/user/show/23135070-laura">Laura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer738104380" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7816241660721430132">This series had great potential, and had a good plot with good (if cliche) characters that felt familiar. Unfortunately, the writing was painful to get through. It&apos;s not that it was bad. I just felt that I had to force myself to read this series that was full of good metaphors, meaningful spiritual anecdotes, and good ethical questions. Most of which were hard to appreciate because reading the whole thing felt like wading through clay.</span>
  <span id="freeText7816241660721430132" style="display:none">This series had great potential, and had a good plot with good (if cliche) characters that felt familiar. Unfortunately, the writing was painful to get through. It's not that it was bad. I just felt that I had to force myself to read this series that was full of good metaphors, meaningful spiritual anecdotes, and good ethical questions. Most of which were hard to appreciate because reading the whole thing felt like wading through clay.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7816241660721430132" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


